node.text: It’s over Anakin, my drone has the high ground! Volcán Pacaya in Guatemala had its biggest eruption in over a decade when I was there this spring and I had the chance to shoot footage of the otherworldly lava flow. Further down, there were dozens of people roasting marshmallows and cooking steaks over the lava. Definitely a night I’ll never forget.

May be an image of nature.

node.text: Morning light in the heart of the Snowy Range. It doesn’t get much more tranquil than this. [Ad] I spent a week traveling across southern Wyoming to showcase some stunning destinations and spread the message of @visitwyoming’s #WYresponsibly campaign. WYresponsibly aims to promote mindful and responsible adventure when traveling our awesome state and it’s a message I am  happy to get behind. It’s important for locals and visitors alike to take care of the magnificent landscapes that cover this state, and everything from respecting fire restrictions to supporting local businesses does just that. Now, it’s your turn! Post a picture of your Wyoming adventure and show me how you travel Wyoming responsibly. Tag #WYresponsibly and @davidmrule and @visitwyoming will send some surprise Wyoming gear to my 2 favorites. See you on the trails!

May be an image of nature.

node.text: No image could possibly do justice at showcasing the beauty of Alaska. It’s a place that can only be experienced. This state blew away my expectations in terms of natural beauty and it felt like I was on a made-up Star Wars planet. There was a new set of mountains to be explored around every corner and I’ve never seen so much blue water in my life. It’s a truly wild and rugged place, and it would take multiple lifetimes to ever see even a fraction of it. To make this place even better, you never run out of light in the summer months and sunsets last for over an hour since the sun rides so close to the horizon. I have a feeling I’ll be coming back up here many more times in the future. 🐻

node.text: Sunrise views from Teton paradise. I just love all the wildflowers that fill the meadows around Jackson, it makes this place feel especially magical. Definitely a view worth waking up at 5AM for. 🌻

node.text: Nothing like a fire show to start off the day! One of the wildest experiences of my entire life was camping less than 3000 meters from an active volcano. After completing the 7 mile hike to the top of Volcán Acatenango, I started hearing rumbling and thought a thunder storm had rolled in.  It wasn’t until reaching the top that I realized all the thunder was actually just Volcán de Fuego hurling it’s fiery guts out. This famous Guatemalan volcano violently erupts every 15-20 minutes and sends lava hurling into the sky. It was lowkey terrifying being so close to this thing but it gave me a newfound respect for nature. If you go to Guatemala and only have time to do one thing, THIS is the thing to do. 🌋

node.text: This was the very first photo I ever took in a foreign country and it remains one of my all time favorites. A little over 2 years ago, I set off to Europe with absolutely no plans and just rode trains and hitchhiked to wherever the journey took me. Having just come from an extremely structured life as a student, it was the first time I felt truly free and it was on this trip that I absolutely fell in love with travel. I can’t wait to get back over to Europe and experience more countries of this incredible continent. 🇬🇧

node.text: I’ve gotta hand it to this place, the views are unreal. Last month, I flew to Guatemala with 3 days notice simply because flights were cheap and it quickly became one of my new favorite countries. There are volcanoes everywhere, people are extremely friendly, and there’s always a new adventure to be found. This pic was from a super nice evening spent at @hobbitenango, a Hobbit-Themed Village overlooking Antigua. There aren’t too many places where you can look at a volcano from a giant stone hand. 🇬🇹

node.text: The Grand Teton Igloo ❄️ This scene has honestly been a dream of mine for a few years now. Every year while growing up, I’d build an igloo in my yard. It was just a fun hobby of mine and I loved being creative with snow. The other year, I thought about how cool it would be to build one at the base of the Tetons, and a few weeks ago @isaacspicz and I made it happen. We spent an entire day forming blocks with plastic office tubs, let them harden overnight, and then assembled the igloo the next day. It turned out way better than expected and it felt so good to get my dream photo. After posting about it on my story, it was so great to see people coming from all over to see our work. The igloo is now just a heap of icy ruins, but it was so much fun while it lasted. 🔥
